Implement the private `insert_sorted/2` function. It takes a list of data points
(each a `{timestamp, value}` tuple) already sorted in ascending timestamp order,
and a new `{timestamp, value}` point to insert. It must return a new list with the
point inserted so the list remains sorted by timestamp in ascending order. Inserting
into an empty list yields a single-element list. When the new point's timestamp is
strictly less than the head's timestamp, it goes in front; otherwise recurse into the
tail so that a point with a timestamp equal to existing ones is placed **after** those
already present (duplicate timestamps keep insertion order). Implement it recursively
using pattern matching, without sorting the whole list.

